A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama's Re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers it a myth, claiming that election fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 that make the process of registration or voting more difficult.
This phenomenon grew after the November 2010 elections, which added 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce pre-voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and remove citizens with a judicial record from their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo IDs issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than $100 to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
A lot more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their identity card with photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote the cards issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have enacted laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
Two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws that abolished voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have enacted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the pre-voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s voters.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of voters made up only 46% of voters voting ahead of time.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters strongly opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The U.S. attorney general intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have enacted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws accounted for 171 of the 270 votes needed by the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Screening for prostate cancer: pass the test or not?
Indeed, the PSA test would sometimes present erroneous results, with false negative results or even false positives, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This makes men who are already reluctant to take screening tests even more hesitant.
Pass the test or not?
We asked for the advice of two specialists.
In studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that you are between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if you are not screened.
So I recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also at higher risk.
The key is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer, offering him the possible options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect life in the long term, and opting instead, in these cases, for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated, because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest active surveillance, and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
Increasingly, criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated are being precisely determined.
I still recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine if we should pass it or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool to assess the pros and cons of PSA testing.
This document can be downloaded (for now, a translation will be available shortly) at: http://ca.movember.com/en/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle recipe to prevent cancer.
Despite advances in research, the adoption of good lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risk of suffering from them.
It is estimated that if everyone ate well and moved around enough, 30% of cancers could be prevented.
“If no one else smoked, this rate would rise to at least 50 percent,” said André Beaulieu, a spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
On the other hand, it is estimated that about 10% of cancers are caused by heredity.
Several remain completely unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, tobacco control remains a priority, despite the decrease in the number of smokers.
Cigarette smoking is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for many others.
This is very damaging to people’s health.
"Even today, there are 1.5 million smokers in Quebec," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouraging fact: 10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer drops by half.
The weight
Overweight and obesity also promote the onset of the disease, according to the CSC.
They would increase the risk of breast, colon and rectal, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancers.
“Research shows that regular physical activity over a lifetime protects against colon cancer.”
The food
The organization also recommends limiting your consumption of red meat.
Too much of it increases the risk of developing colorectal cancer.
Charcuteries too, and they should be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogenic substances.
"The latter can damage the cells of the body and lead to the development of cancer," it is explained.
The Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin supplements and cancer.
Their research, however, is not conclusive at the moment.
Studies on vitamin E are contradictory, according to the SCC.
While one saw a decrease in prostate cancer risk, another saw an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer is also unclear.
In addition, Mr. Beaulieu stresses the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
“Passing a screening test doesn’t give cancer.”
The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but data is still lacking to be perfectly certain.
Suppose, however, that it is the Higgs, since the chances of making a mistake seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you'll hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly consisting of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they may indeed be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be in some way related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at this precise place, a bit like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" for that boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could wrinkle the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never stand on its own on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, tiens) do not.
Now, what does all this research "can bring," Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancy between the observations and predictions of the MS.
There are also many who are eager to find one, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug some holes of the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, proposing no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-ops!).
But such gaps have not been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work was about to unleash.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed), in 1962 – at first the laser was rather seen as a “lab gadget”.
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as an “eye” to all the digital cameras in the world, and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics 2009.
This of course does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die... <0x7C> The Duty
With its Dying with Dignity Commission, Quebec has recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
In this essential area, however, much remains to be done.
Duty tried to take a closer look at it.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him had left him a two-year break.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," he says, half-fig half-grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Going back to the stage of the child, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept regression, he notes.
For, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life prognosis of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I have no desires in life,” she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the coming days, however, she awaits a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, we provide body care and food assistance.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little when we know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person will agree to provide mouth care with brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, a beer was served to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but are not the same.
Alongside a 93-year-old man savoring his last family gathering in the yard, tightly stuck in his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," said Dr Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a care home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that causes several physicians specialized in palliative care to fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before they agree to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients are asking to die only because they are not receiving the right care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are hard at work on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard’s life expectancy was already minimal when she dropped out of strenuous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
Yet she told me I was finished!
No all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not complying with their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is equivalent to sleeping the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadicly or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me”, it means “I want to be relieved”.
