With Bitcoin, Pay and Sell Without Banks
Just the opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from peer to peer.
Approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a high of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2, five months later, before returning today around a dozen dollars (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
Yet, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “in competition with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to progress in a video game that you earn by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this type of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both account book depositories, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the manner of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger, broadcast throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through solving a mathematical challenge launched to computers, and whose winner, sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file hashing, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, for fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves some margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also increased with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
“The flaw used is not about the protocol itself,” said Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, “giant balances” were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which come back cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
They just need to communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of questioning of hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to come through, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, in case of success of this currency.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow in late 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take back possession of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting everything from us.
It is mainly the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them as terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former refugee leaders in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in Soviet times.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, they will no longer be so when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the top of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was done in order.
The convoys of trucks and armored vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban raid on Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country with fire and blood, because of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country had then been perceived as a sort of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overwhelmed by the al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved these days.
Former mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban are joining in the desire to keep women in an inferior position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They moved into businessmen, seizing government land to sell it to build land to refugees returned from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. subcontracting contracts.
They disregarded themselves; most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
