The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: high school for girls and boys, department of French at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to achieve the impossible task of making aids and offensive actions coincide, a "civil-military actions" service of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), suppressed in 2012, has carried out, and has been carried out by a small French NGO, numerous collective interest work and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of villages.
This work, greedy of local labor, was able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase of cultivable areas.
What will we leave as a memory, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of the very harsh local living conditions in these valleys, which are often more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The embassy received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa Province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which the farmers told me they wanted, a small, well-controlled and directly affecting civilian aid would have to be maintained in their favour.
A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is a new poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration, which grants it provisionally full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this House two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, several times amended, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his “autocratic delirium”, continuing to “betray his word” and “trompe the law”.
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that obliges the Brothers to renounce their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in favour, as he claimed in an interview with the US weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote stems from the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these supposedly to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had knocked on the door, believing that they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, the articles were most often unanimously voted on.
Commentators were also amused by the fact that one of the only divergences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, with some members of the committee believing that the constituent's pendulum was poorly settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, article 2 remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," respond the Liberals, who see it only as a blow to communication.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see in it the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system," tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be an ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from the religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are markedly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights groups.
The latter also expressed their concerns about the text, which they considered to be liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, there is no longer any article that echoes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak last night on television, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has identified five great reasons to visit Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
You must visit: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever enters these “baptismal funds” will be touched by divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Street of Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia fortress (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world stands, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place of the Jews: the Lamentation Wall which constitutes the remainder of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Massada fortress, a former refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins lie on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old beliefs say that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
Impossible to visit them all in a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (the parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
There are mainly paintings by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel’s three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not drop below 21° while the air temperature can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure-coloured water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived here a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk in the narrow streets that are named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take photoshoots from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you are going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The trip in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scale-free fish and dishes composed of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk the air haughty.
We can see them sleeping at night on the roofs of parked cars.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be enjoyed.
Renting a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 per day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Entrance to the museum costs on average 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has language, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists controversy over what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling “false” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are Central Asian nationals: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since 1 December, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to pass the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by Members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what is it going to give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, say the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to cross paths with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" in an overcrowded cottage where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and papers and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
“In their homes, they are promised something, and when they arrive, they are cheated, they are taken their passport, and they do not get their salary,” said Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of Tajikistan’s migration service.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to come and make money in Russia are confident that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to attend even a reasonable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children, let alone to dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
“You feel diminished and diminished.”
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be aimed only at migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no examination or official work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or Defend to Enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and always the language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us for 100, 200 rubles, to buy cigarettes, tea," Umed Khushkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
“Be quick, don’t sluggish, and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language exam certificates have already been confiscated by Federal Migration Service employees.
Forged papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not consider them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of exams had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper towels.”
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to pass the exam at the first stroke time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The proportion of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against the bearers of civilian weapons.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether shootings at weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow jurist Dmitry Vinogradov, which killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullet weapons in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining the license to carry weapons by increasing it from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Law would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is pleased to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Internet in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were registered over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that strengthening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow today for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the dissemination of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for arms is supplied via several channels.
There are five main channels, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking control of weapons
The first is "the military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen from law enforcement by criminals.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal guns go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of them have often suffered explosions.
"Tested versions indicate that some fires were set on purpose to cover up the deficit," he said.
For Baranets, the arms manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private arms factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” said one expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Studies.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "due to employees whose work is related to weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "clandestine excavations".
A salesman and consultant at an armory who asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these specialists of the clandestine excavation; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will pick up the new goods from military warehouses.
The person purchases a unit through a sign, for example a TT pistol.
We deliver it to him by passing the merchandise through a wire mesh.
“He transports it to the city and sells it for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>900 per unit with two chargers,” he says.
“It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a purchase of control from illegal arms dealers,” the seller adds.
"Like in a luxury shop"
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I checked sites, blogs, until a guy came up and offered me to come to the Begovaya station where someone would take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun was given to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the salesman. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are vendors in the markets, but there you also have to come saying, for example, "From that person, who asked me to report that his daughter lost a tooth."
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
The young ones are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Victor Baranets attempted to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s as he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
He was given a photo album in which there was "everything we want".
“I thought I was in a luxury store,” recalls the soldier.
There is no secret for the buyer, explains Baranets, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller to the forest and set up a target.
“I am allowed to shoot and when I am convinced that the weapon is working well, we start negotiating,” the expert describes.
A shop from his couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
For this, you do not need any documents and no one to meet.
"It is enough to have a precise sum of money," the ad reads on the website "Buy a pistol or a combat machine gun".
