U.S.: Fast-food and supermarket workers on strike
Nearly a quarter of U.S. teens go through a cashier’s job at McDonald’s
In recent days, a wave of protests has mounted against the low wages practiced by Walmart supermarkets and the famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict if this wave is going to increase in magnitude or slow down quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Along with the rise in modest wages for basic employees at Walmart and in fast food chains, protest organizers are seeking unions.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, the "Black Friday", at a time when a flood of payrolls that seized millions of inhabitants fell on America and sometimes triggered clashes.
On that day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs to organize strike pickets with unions and left-wing activists in the stores of the company whose products are aimed at consumers of the modest and middle classes.
Walmart markets everything from diapers to shotguns to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paid employees at Walmart shop only in their workplaces.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply because of the low salaries of its employees.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example the lack of forklifts or portable scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests demanded a salary increase, they complained that the price of medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $30 to $100 per month.
For the basic employee at Walmart who earns $9.5 an hour, that’s an amount he can’t afford.
Scientists at the California University of Berkley show that if Walmart raised the average hourly wage to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That's 1.1% more than he's currently spending.
If Walmart were to transfer the entire wage increase to the shoulders of consumers, each run in the store would cost them an extra 46 cents.
They will spend $12.39 more in one year than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in stores from 8 a.m. to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over that period 5,000 items per second.
Its cashiers have made a total of 100 million transactions for Black Friday.
The company's spokesman Dan Fogleman assured in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post that in all "less than five" Walmart employees had left their positions and that the protest was only a "com' operation among many others" on the part of the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
The protests continued this week in New York and were not about Walmart stores (in this progressive city, they are not very popular, which is why they are not yet established there) but about McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s advertises selling billions of servings and then they don’t even give you sick leave and don’t pay you for the work you’ve done honestly!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the City Council of New York
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York law is $7.25 per hour.
Fast foods increase them over time, but on average, its basic employees earn $8.90 per hour in New York.
No one touches less than them in this city.
It's inconceivable for me to live with that amount in New York.
There was a time when almost a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald’s after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wished to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain about having to live on that salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the forum of the Wall Street Journal there are comments that say that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know what you are going to feed them with.
Protesters who launched the movement Thursday at 6:30 a.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and on Madison Avenue demanded that cashiers and fast food cooks be paid at least $15 an hour, more than twice the current minimum wage.
They also called for the creation of trade unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing and punishing union protesters by bullying or firing.
However, administration rarely simplifies their lives.
For a trade union, seizing fast food remains a difficult task, and that, for concrete reasons.
One of the main ones is the extraordinary turnover of staff.
They don't agree
Other tumultuous protests were taking place near several other fast food chains.
The highlight of the protest was the mid-day rally near Times Square’s McDonald’s with the intervention of several local Democratic politicians, including City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said, “McDonald’s announces selling billions of servings and then they don’t even give you sick leave and pay you for the work you did honestly!”
The protesters were supported by other prominent New York Democrats, including Mayoral Candidate Bill De Blasio who said that “we all need to support fast food employees so they get a fair wage and the economic well-being that every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times characterized this event as the most significant event the fast food industry has seen in its entire history.
But only a few hundred people participated, not to mention that not all of them were fast-food employees, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is currently difficult to say whether this spark of mass movement will make small ones.
