Lately, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it is clear from the interview with Shahram Izadi, director of the interactive 3D technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, that for the scientists of this company, glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained so far to the pixels on the flat screen and sometimes to the touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead and guess the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect because everyone is interested in commanding by gesture.
- What does the future hold for us too?
- Although Kinect has made the interaction physical, a lot of things take place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information entry has been improved (the system receives more data), but performance, for now, not really.
We're trying to change that, and we're working on real 3D imaging systems running on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to bring out the computer world in ours, in the physical world, to make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds him.
Thus, we will be able to complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And to begin with, let’s get rid of those stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command?
It’s appreciated, but isn’t it overrated?
We cannot say that this is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because we do not always want to inform others of our actions or intentions.
In fact, each type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to order the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the camera, but by a bracelet worn in the hand that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to give you this can?
You would do it with words and with gestures.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it's gonna be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or can not do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
It can be, for example, laser sensors, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and it is very important.
- If we're interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don't you like about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth or anything else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we are based in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but rather the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all current technologies are quite good, this adds work to the designers of algorithms.
It is necessary to keep in mind the resolution according to the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche of our Redmond lab gave the touch of the sensors a steady processing delay of between 1 and 100 <0xCE><0xBC>s, the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a camera of this type in my work, but not needing to touch, to have more frames per second.
Shouldn’t we increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a usual visible field sensor.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
A lot of cameras could solve this problem...
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a soft product similar to Kinect, play with the camera curve and see how it could help define the locations.
