- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the simple mortal.
There is a problem on which opponents of this idea point the finger: there is no tactile sensation!
The hands feel nothing.
What responses is your group preparing for this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth might very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image support.
It records the pressure perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really meant to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed to a specific point where the finger is located and which gives you the feeling, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
