Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with Earthlings on board set off in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how to continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
"It's about Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500 .
We can only live there at very high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We started to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were carried out on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from the terrestrial varieties.
Then we put insects into orbit, small breeding Drosophila flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
We get at the exit a chick quite normal.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find a support, it has to get on its legs and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
Finding no support, the chicks agitated in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We opened their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological “miniature ark” with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the biosatellite " Bion " will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. You have to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to reproduce directly in space.
It's no small matter.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of this in principle.
Homo sapiens possess abstract thought, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
Women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Tereshkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has of most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would stand after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the theft.
“No one was answering that question,” said Vakhtang Vachnadze, a retired rocket and space scientist.
In June 1964, just one year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova gave birth to a baby girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after being in orbit twice and even working in extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during orbital flights," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valery Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Hydrology Laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Centre: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train on extra-vehicular trips.
Water imitates weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but nevertheless a foreign environment, for infants, it is their real element.
Small amphibious humans seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby evolves about 9 months into the lymphatic fluid in her mother's belly, it is easier for her to get used to the water afterwards.
This is in principle logical, because from its birth until its first bath, it takes only 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the newborn child the weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the thrust capacity of the baby is lost.
All right, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
We can of course prepare a birth in a special room, the woman will manage to get it out.
"What then?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite us to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the earthly attraction, the organism does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
You can’t dress an infant like an adult with a special wetsuit for training.
It will simply be deprived of its vital needs.
"And this experience that we would envisage in this case imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will result in the return to Earth of a disabled child, totally misfit," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, in time this will become a reality, as Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their space-born offspring.
