At the meeting of the oversight committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German draft in which the public procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was it specifically about?
This is a parallel check that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and a practice proper follow it.
We have put all this together, and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps "stronger and of better quality", however, according to some parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to continually develop increasingly detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote oneself to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project really help you and what does it mean for you?
A common control of this kind should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those who look for loopholes will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar institution to our CSI or a different mode of organization?
As far as institutions are concerned, like the ISC, the similarly organized Bundesrechnungshof operates there, it also has a somewhat differently constituted council, but these two institutions proceed fundamentally in a similar way.
The competences are also, to some extent, similar, but with a nuance in relation to our system: Germany being a federal structure, it also has accounts of this type at the level of the different Länder.
The HRB can only control federal money, which corresponds to the resources of the state.
The public funds managed in our country by the regions and the municipalities, are there controlled at the level of the accounts of the Länder.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model but one can certainly not say that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, certainly not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country that we see as a model also faces a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, right?
As regards national legislation, what has the amendment to the Public Procurement Act meant for you as an institution, are its effects already being felt?
As this amendment has entered into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our control operations.
As we carry out ex-post checks, we have to count on a certain delay.
Our comments concern only, for the time being, the process of preparing future checks - we have launched a new "mismanagement risk detection" instrument with which we have screened almost 14,000 public contracts - these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been changed as well as the conditions of certain types of tendering procedures and so on.
So do you consider the passage of this law to be more of an advantage or an additional burden on the administration?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that may arise is that these rules become more stringent and it is not possible to respect them.
Already under the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the Regional Council, in the case of regional operational programmes) was forcing the audited subjects to accept that any breach of the Market Law would mean a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really helpful to make the law more stringent in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequences on the decision-making process.
