Poland and the Cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern Bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's journey into space, however, began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always find understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture of A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The so-called Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned astronautic propagator, his contribution being rewarded notably by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
In 1925 a draisin was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisin.
The only information known about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the preserved documents that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish aeronautical society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problème, in which there are four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965 succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Utility Works Act.
This decision has raised a lively debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means that the various economic entities and national economic systems are in constant conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and the free (unlimited) movement of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate a tension on prices.
The term should be understood as meaning the following: a producer endeavours, by importing goods sold at low prices, to resist economic competition by making the price of the competitor more expensive, with the aim of taking away a greater share of the market and thereby increasing his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either transferring production abroad, buying cheaply, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no liability for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the State necessarily increase.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that there is no need to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without regard to social collapse.
This is mainly manifested in the amendments of the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the price dictate of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, to the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
The result is increasing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In the FRG, there have been for years public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of these people is already counted in millions.
In the context of the increasing competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite commonplace that wage earners receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a surcharge in order for them to reach the vital minimum.
Such a scandal has, for example, been brought up in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of practically all the southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day they will be forced to invest in private life.
The question must be asked: where does this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media are tired of claiming that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the led economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence and even, according to its own selfish interests, direct politics and, by the same token, the entire state.
The answer to this question is without a doubt yes.
Proof of this is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby in every state.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the FRG, the situation is such that due to a lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of legislation to firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State had long been in full decay and functions were attributed by violence.
Bribes, favors obtained illegally, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
Under-the-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold"... ... "Honest people did not seek in any way to obtain functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls".... ' It really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was a real pompistic but the 'remedies' was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose a man...
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is an unprecedented decadence of elites, with no effort to make profound reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a sort of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today’s elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future losses of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today as well as the crimes against humanity as we have known them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Utility Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and internally in Europe, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investments in the economy, increase citizen influence over government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
