People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how did you come up with the idea of running for president?
It's not being a senator or a president that matters to me.
If everything went smoothly in our country, I wouldn’t be a candidate anywhere.
But I can no longer bear to see how the country has been looted for the last twenty years, that thieves are not under lock and key, and taxes and retirement ages are rising.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something that I don't like, then I try to come up with a solution for it to change.
And since I am over forty years old and independent, a member of no party, I have no other way of influencing the situation than to stand in presidential or senatorial elections.
You entered the Senate but you quickly set out for the Castle (N.D.T.: seat of the presidency).
Do you not turn your backs on those who have chosen you?
I've always said that I'll start the battle for the Castle according to the results of the senatorial elections.
Later, I made it clear that if I were elected a senator, I would stand in the presidential election.
My goal is not function, it is only an instrument that allows me to realize my vision.
That is why I need the greatest influence and the broadest mandate.
