For example, it has been said about me that I bribe journalists or that I was the adviser to Ji<0xC5><0x99>í Paroubek.
Let’s come to your visions.
You have begun the struggle for the Castle with the themes of the material and criminal responsibility of politicians and retroactive tax returns over twenty million [CZK].
To that end, you must change the law.
As president, you do not have such power and only the Senate as a whole can propose laws.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When, as a citizen, I pushed for the profession of a tour guide, I was successful.
The problem is politics: when someone comes from the left or the right with a good project, it is knowingly rejected and it delays citizens.
As an independent, non-party member, I am much more likely to get the support of all parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without categorization and partisan dogma, to take from each side what is best for our country and implement it.
Do you see yourself as a man of the left or the right?
From a Czech point of view, I have the impression that people place me rather to the left.
For me, whether it’s a little to the left or to the right, it’s not really important.
For me, the important thing is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not that people are left or right, but to bring people together.
I always support any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or SDGs, and I act equally impartially against bad ideas.
Do you get angry when someone says you’re a populist?
But does what you said not prove it?
