The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, this building is indeed beautiful."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one goes voluntarily to one of these crappy libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeper town that has nothing attractive on the doorstep of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a mockery on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, baffled and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the brazen, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments by a: "common darling!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain sprouted from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and adjoining houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this small dull town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of staggering ugliness, whose white facades invite to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural edifice in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under a cheese bell.
It is true that an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you step on the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lamps speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, library shelves are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We completely upset the classical spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been deftly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panels, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircases.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager with the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes of a millimetre thickness have been used for years as substrates in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and it saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun illuminates the interior only briefly, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted crosswise relative to the glass facade serve as a sun visor, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “finally found soul.”
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure allowed to fill the voids of the library that was not yet completely filled (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
Architect Winy Maas once said, “There is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s just for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and under-educated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans need to play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians’ request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
What's the point?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Eventually, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans clashed on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are still trying to find this role, but they are on the path to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany has first of all important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hurt public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Is Germany harming its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto in a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the country’s political configuration, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other hand?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing on the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will play a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
