"Brand Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, she's not sure she'd win.
“It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing’s Far East property law firm.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a folder containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell practically only counterfeits.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: its constituents charge it with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a related brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women are designated who marry rich men.
Chinese officials say they have nothing to blame.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch said.
“The brand is sweetened, the uniqueness disappears, the damage to the reputation is enormous.”
Financial losses and court costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 billion, the world’s third-largest and fastest-growing luxury goods market.
However, it is not easy to erase dubious registrations from the trademark registry and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch referred to the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period, the criticized denomination had become a "market reality".
Pattloch tells us that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought out concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the purchaser of Volvo, used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW, but the dispute was resolved and Geely had to modify it.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost to plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the famous crocodile’s gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing admits, however, to have experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year, the office would have moved from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a normality regained".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 cases of this type would have been closed, representing a 75% increase over the previous year.
However, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and this means that China is for the tenth time in a row at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fee.
In other words, each registration earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs a lot more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg illustrates.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
Admittedly, the Germans were able to obtain that the illegal manufacture of vehicle components be suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, chairman of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Trademark Office therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg was successful in the next two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds, "the procedure is long, arduous and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the Archives Service has even had to review the acts of the past 100 years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party a "big six-digit sum in euros" to settle the dispute.
“That’s where we see what it means to us,” Wentzler said.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region ensured the exploitation of the unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file the name Freudenberg in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Watch is necessary."
Pattloch and he advised German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, rather foreigners should "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the final act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
