Many points of the draft Constitution are subject to interpretation
Another problematic aspect is the likely continuation of military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's reign, these courts tried to suppress opponents.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained by the military.
The state must also protect “the true nature of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values.”
From a legal point of view, the formulation is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of art cinematography and literature.
In other words, it would simply be censorship.
Moreover, no article expressly guarantees equality between men and women.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
On the other hand, the article does not define what an offense is or how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording suggesting that it is forbidden to "offend people".
Is it enough to draw a caricature of the president or to tell a joke to the detriment of a lawman?
Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the project that Morsi submits to the vote and which, in his own words, will "very soon" be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians.
"The revolution is coming back"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of Islamists.
On Friday evening, tens of thousands of protesters gathered in unusual unity in Cairo’s Tahrir Square, promising to bring down Sharia law before it comes into force.
“The revolution is reborn and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, who finished third in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution is “to be thrown into the dustbins of history.”
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi's supporters of wanting to foment a "putsch against democracy".
