“We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet expiated,” said Khaled Ali, an Egyptian politician and member of the opposition.
In addition, several judges said they did not want to monitor the referendum, which would result in its nullity.
“The Qur’an is our Constitution.”
For its part, the well-organized Muslim Brotherhood called for a counter-demonstration not in Tahrir Square as a precautionary measure, but on the other side of the Nile, where a large prayer was organized in front of Cairo University.
The veiled women and supporters of the Salafists, who participated in large numbers, chanted: "the people demand the application of the law of God."
“Clean up our country!” they asked Morsi, claiming that “the Qur’an [was] their Constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty in the symbolic Tharir Square, where everything began, would soon have engendered a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Obviously, this is what Morsi’s supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said opponents of the draft constitution, along with its supporters, had spoken out loud.
According to them, now is the time to let the people decide by the ballot box the direction that the country must take.
The project of the Islamists will certainly win the majority.
“Human rights are not mentioned once.”
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process that should have lasted until February and encompassed all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) had defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their view of the world, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
That's why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
"And now, the term is not even pronounced once in the new Constitution," he laments during his interview with the Welt am Sonntag.
The extension of Morsi’s powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of the rules of democracy and will engender a new dictatorship in Egypt.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto strips him of all his powers,” Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels neglected, including by the international community, which looks at the battle between different political ideologies on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
It could pay off.
A protester in Tharir Square warns: "you are giving birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control."
Norway’s rakfisk: Is it the most odorous fish in the world?
The five million people who populate Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to the locals' appetite for an extremely odorous fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty soccer clothing.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most popular dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this ubiquitous smell permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can last up to a year.
When darkness sets in and it is cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, a local full-time firefighter also known as "Rakfisk General", who is responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” Havard adds.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid making it pass under your nose, it's not bad - it reminds me of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels and then salted in the fall.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - undoubtedly with the senses diminished by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mainly emigrating to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, albeit odorous, element of Norway’s past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>10 each.
Norway is not often featured in international news, which is not to her displeasure.
Here, people are unwilling to talk about Anders Breivik, the extremist right-wing racist who shot and killed 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the “22 July incident.”
The Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own could have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
“But oil isn’t the only reason for our success,” says Anna, our blonde-haired waitress with piercing blue eyes, the image of Nordic well-being, with a tray of rakfisk in her hand.
We are - as you say - cautious people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything except a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries threw money out the window in the years leading up to the international financial crisis, Norway kept its stock market tight.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy," Anna says.
"Without forgetting the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand under the snow and line up to buy food - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a burger made of élan, a real discovery, is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where one serves rakfisk for dinner and where one can vote for the best of them - or perhaps for the most smelly of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It looks like a Eurovision contest.
"What score did you give the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish emanations.
The Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a difficult start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, BBC’s Will Grant looks at the difficulties ahead and the people’s expectations, which are numerous.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are rampant in normal times, a security barrier has been put in place since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nonetheless, the goal was not to prevent people from going to their work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico's economy is doing well, the results owed to outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is plagued by a drug war that has already claimed the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populous and sprawling state that encloses the capital. On his favorite land, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic municipality of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The locals attribute it to the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city, you can take one of the new motorways of M Pena Nieto, a major improvement has been made to these roads, once bumpy and full of crevices.
Plaques bearing his name are hung outside a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are counting on him to bring about lasting change," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a member of Congress and of the PRI's Pena Nieto party.
In terms of security and economy in particular, we hope for a real change that our country so much needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years spent outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party regarding Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects criticism from opponents who accuse the new president of lack of charisma.
He is an entire man, very committed, with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, he knows how to listen.
However, this is not always the image that people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobblestone streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more egregious.
Hidden under highway bridges, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City.
And the problems in the municipality are also concrete and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called to the rescue to fight drug gangs in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is particularly severe.
In a disaster area, the bodies of dozens of women murdered in the last two years have been found on the landfill edge.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Pena Nieto was governor, a much higher rate than in the very violent city of Ciudad Juarez - a place infamous for the number of innocent women who were killed there.
Detractors of Mr. Pena Nieto, say that at best, he failed to stem the problem of murders perpetrated against women when he was in office.
At worst, they accuse his administration of refusing to see reality in the face.
In a concrete house, typical of this dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back her tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
The official version mentions a suicide committed by Mariana in 2010.
However, her family believes she was killed by her partner.
"When I arrived at her house, it seemed to me that her body had been washed," says Señora Buendia.
Signs indicated that she had been beaten, and the cadaveric stiffness had already begun.
As her mother tells the story, a picture of Mariana dresses the wall, next to a cross with the word: Justice.
However, this is exactly what the family was refused.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want us to accept what they say and keep quiet.
“But it’s not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has made a promise that he will make it his priority during his tenure.
"I hope he will be as good as when he was governor," Olvera said in Valle del Bravo, a congressman.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained about ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning was allegedly subjected to while in detention.
The trial is about Manning’s detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's abduction took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of causing the largest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. military, has missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During cross-examination with Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defense filed an application demanding that the Manning case be closed on the grounds that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning expressed his desire to commit suicide while in detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers had filled out after meeting with Manning, during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he had received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had within the prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had expressed concerns orally about certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the issues raised.
“They wrote ‘no problems’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I hadn’t raised any problems,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed to indicate a “risk of injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay, and I wanted to be removed from that status ... so I could have a better quality of life from my perspective,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps base military prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- alone.
Manning also added that the only items he had at his disposal were a mattress, blanket, flip-flops, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also made it clear that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that he could see his face.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning’s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after he was forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge’s questions Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard’s order that he had to drop his blanket that could have hidden his nakedness, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop her.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his brief or flip-flops to injure himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he had during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is convicted before a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning is considering pleading guilty to the lesser offenses and fighting for the dropping of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defense-related information.
If all the charges are detained, he faces life imprisonment.
The Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many have been forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame those who left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says that Mexican-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of the customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two routes: one for the "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood still for several seconds, not knowing which line to go to.
I grew up in central California, where I’ve been called the “Mexican” all my life.
It’s an ethnic qualifier, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves “Irish,” or my friends in New York when they call themselves “Italian.”
Then I became "Mexico-American."
But here it was Mexico.
And on the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualification or a bond.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, well enough to handle an interview in either language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of an Aboriginal, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and headed to the "Foreigners" queue.
I thought about that moment of the week when the new Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited President Obama in the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their favorite themes are immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than take risks in the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada, and create a trade union on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, although he has not provided further details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and filled with bitterness.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory in writing at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, and not minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how Americans are undermining the sovereignty of their neighbor.
And the children of Montezuma are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is the one that the country has with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about bitterness?
There's a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not.
The only reason that explains the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at some point in our family tree, a person, perhaps a parent or grandparent, did not find any opportunity in Mexico and had to go to the North.
And most of the time, this person corresponded to a typical profile -- dark skin, poorly educated, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even if we are currently living the American dream, that we have been to good schools and we have good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that this is the American dream we are living, and not the dream of Mexicans.
Our identity is sometimes troubled, but our loyalty is obvious.
We grant it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that a part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is reciprocal.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they hair us as if we were individuals of lower and not sufficiently Mexican stock.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we would not find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but as lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans, because Mexicans are more firmly claiming their identity and Mexican-Americans are upset.
Although she is a U.S. citizen, she has a sense of being part of two countries.
Moreover, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel like they are part of one country or another.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we're considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and some of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as makeshift ambassadors for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our fellow Americans that Mexico is a superb country that we absolutely must visit and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
It's not going to happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, given the pervasive wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to take care of yourself, amigos.
That's normal.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still want them for the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexicans" than I thought.
Old quarrels, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments for who started persist, dozens of buildings have been crushed to dust; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza landed near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although the Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their former conflict, all around them, the Middle East is in full mutation.
The Arab Spring has shattered everything, whether we like it or not, the Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Yet there is every reason to think that it could help them get out of this deadly impasse.
A war that does not make any losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
While the November 21 ceasefire continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will boast of forcing the Israelis to give up, even though Gaza has been beaten.
Having killed some of its leaders and driven Gaza’s 1.7 million people back into one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their rivals Fatah, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing stronger, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a burgeoning regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken up the cause for Hamas; as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s richest and most dynamic states.
Hamas members are cheering and saying that the Islamist crescent is bending around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah militia exercises its dominance, through Syria, where Islamist-leaning rebels can overthrow Bashar El Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on the southern flank of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and most central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood are Hamas cousins, and their leaders are more easily reliant on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important player that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hardliners will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been put back in the box.
The missile interception system dubbed the Iron Dome has proven its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America is renewing its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel prospered, notably under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, notably thanks to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality in international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more bellicose party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has the good side.
Why pamper these damn Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they were running the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind that wall and hit them as soon as they get their heads out.
Perhaps hardliners will win; but it may be that the Arab Spring is changing the game.
Even if the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere have little appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments to settle their economies.
Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to secure a ceasefire, which bodes well -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is doomed to explode one day in Israeli-occupied territories — much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to ring Hamas will have a diplomatic price.
Both sides need to be pushed by those from the outside.
The answer remains that advocated by the reasonable people on each side, and by most of the outside world, and by this newspaper: two states, with a surrender of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One small and short-term hope is that the ceasefire will provide an opportunity for outsiders to defend this cause.
Egypt, which must now work to halt the flow of arms to Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in accordance with the 1967 borders with land exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also put pressure on Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute much more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal for a pseudo-state at the United Nations.
Mr. Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to establish one.
This is a very narrow view.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This requires a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The laws for neutral cigarette packets have come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of diseased organs cover the dark green packages that are all identical, regardless of brand
This law that came into force in Australia is a world first, logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrific photos of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose illnesses were caused by their parents’ smoking.
Apart from the various photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all the packages.
It is the world's strictest tobacco packaging regime.
The Australian federal government said the goal was to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous representation.
Studies have shown that if people have not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start.
“Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that revealed, for example, that children associated the crown of a logo with a princess.
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has lobbied against this law.
