For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the earth's bowels solidifies on contact with air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilograms, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, to a turtle-like pace, keeping balance and measuring their steps so as not to trip and fall into the precipice.
