Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times as much as he would earn in the fields.
“The income of miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the bearer who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I converted her to Java.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Driven by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the work of a mule.
He shares an unhealthy lumbering with other porters, gets up every day at two in the morning because sulfur does not stop gushing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater and lights up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not touch one under the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) surcharge per camera, in addition to the entry of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not humans,” said Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent carrier who has worked at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since leaving college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can" because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases ... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders.
By balancing the basket on his back, the 53-year-old Unainik can only carry 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail invaded by weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik says, opening his mouth and revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but the perpetual misery from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame this lack of children on the career, stress and cost of accessing property.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem implausible that these lyrics come from an advertisement for mint lozenges, but despite that, or perhaps thanks to that, the video spread like a powder keg on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a polychinelle in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way through this advertising.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill "their national duty."
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it fun and entertaining.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt that this was a theme that we had to address.
We knew the government had tried several things like throwing perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, what could be more creative to solve this problem than to make it a rap song?
1.2 children
The government of Singapore does not take it so lightly.
He spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, according to its national population distribution, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
So why do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, said it was due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family building,” she said.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound in barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese people who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in Singapore experienced its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the election, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to prevent the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has begun to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun controlling the number of small apartments, known as the "shoe box", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage promoters wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are being built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to promoters, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to propose too many small dwellings in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If so much is that these new regulations could be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they are not going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it off,” says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But for me, it’s important to be able to have my money and my time,” says another 20-year-old.
Men and women cite their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
Thus, although the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of private life that we can protect from intrusion".
What is the private domain for children under 16 years of age?
How to apply this definition in daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces by posting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term “something very personal” on a personal level and “password and username” when they applied it to social networks.
“I won’t reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” says 10-year-old Jorge, when he tries to explain the meaning of the term private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
“These are very secret secrets, my mother may know them but not everyone,” he says.
On FB, I post cool pictures or games.
I also talk to my friends.
“I’m not going to share one of my photos or someone who would be an idiot,” he said.
The boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are family.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they’re answering me, I’m just posting them,” he adds.
“Social networks are fun, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends, quickly,” he says.
He said he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
Neither will he trust anyone who would recommend a stranger to him.
The case of José, 14, is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not to know 20 of the people registered on his list of friends.
“It doesn’t bother me because we have something in common, music for example,” he says.
According to the boy, no one made any advances to him or asked for his address or telephone number.
“If they pressured me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account,” he said.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences known today as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A friend of mine has been hacked into a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He just passed it on in a private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to set up his account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or upset.
“Even though I know it’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that, to guide children and adolescents, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a way to search for information, but with the emergence of these sites, the rule of the game has changed," she said.
Porras points out that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book "Natives and Digital Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are the ones, the children and young people who were born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we ourselves are learning,” she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a definite criterion on what they should or should not disclose, publish or say at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so."
“We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she added.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach confidentiality to children and adolescents is to use questions that make them think.
“Saying not to do it is useless,” she says.
Then Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to publish a photo of you like a friend you posted?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you’re doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
These are the same rules.
"Outside of the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social networks," she said.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education advisor, says it is essential for parents to read the terms of use of social networks thoroughly.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The Unasur summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Foreign Ministry and the presidency initially indicated that it would be leaked after the summit closes, then said it would be published at any time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the summit’s “final statement,” but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although it was urgently requested by the press, it had not released the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited to the maximum the obtaining of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court that settles a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the lawsuit that Lima filed against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing today before this international court,” President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of international controversies, treaties and courts,” Piñera said, shaking hands with Humala, standing next to the two countries’ flags.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from UNASUR since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He said actions would be put in place to improve “cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, cheap internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters.”
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and foresee a better future for our peoples”, concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," he said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the transverse axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
“We will review all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask to have a discussion with this country,” he said.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, in the framework of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
“South America must learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship,” says Rafael Correa.
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa said today that the creation of a common citizenship was an objective for which "South America, in this case, should take an example on Europe".
President Correa, who attended the 6th summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, said on state television, TV Peru, that Europeans "had killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but that they were now almost a homeland."
