And if Sweden, as fully permitted by its legislation, and as it has already done in other cases, interviewed Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or interviewed him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of freedom of the press and made it clear that what he did not tolerate was "the mediocrity, the bad faith and the lies that undermine freedom of expression".
“The greatest enemies of press freedom are not malevolent or perverse politicians but bad journalists on the pay of greed, blackmail and extortion,” he said.
