Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay within Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the body "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality "it destroys the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considers that the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty, is "perfectly relevant".
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We must solve them as a whole to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the proper resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile within the same tribunal and said that it is "beneficial for Latin America to seize international forums if the two countries agree to accept a judgment as firm as it is".
Referring to the possibility of his nomination as a candidate in the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he noted that he saw this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa said that if he lost the February 2013 primaries, he would retire from public life.
On a personal level, power has never interested me, but in situations as unfair as those in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one guaranteeing this eventual victory, but we must accept this responsibility," he said.
If I win, it will be my last term in office and then I will retire from politics.
If we ever lose, I will too.
“It’s my decision,” he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just talked to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse of President Chávez's state of health," he said.
