AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed to be HIV positive.
"It's as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to inquire about him and his hard work was such that he has just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 90s, where there were a lot of doubts, little choice of treatment and more stigmas.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him “because he was speechless.”
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, “depleted” their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes for reference that this information was validated in a scientific year in April.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a life-threatening disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system involvement that patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better rates for those not using drugs reaching up to 50 years and up to 200 years.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who receives an HIV-positive diagnosis at age 25, "as long as he remains under control, he can live without problems up to 75 years," the scientist said.
In order to put this progress in context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of deaths from AIDS has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients identified in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral medicines has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we have never run out of drugs, the problem is that patients are coming to very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they are learning it at advanced stages of the disease.
Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, we must offer screening tests in a massive way, to all people who ask for it.
The specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffered from a complication of the sarcoma.
Everything changes when you learn you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know.
“If I’m going to die, it’s better that I have fun three times a week,” they say, but that’s not my case.
The change was beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, his parents know only that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, just like everyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and to the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Let them take the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of one hundred, it is very good, but it results, that even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, the journalist says.
He proposes to redirect this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at the counters, but that they be found in public toilet dispensers and in places where young people frequent.
This is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of paying for the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
“This is not how sexuality works, it’s best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,” he said.
Numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The State is the 4th state in the country in the number of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in the number of HIV patients.
92% of contamination is sexual, 6% is bloodborne and 2% is perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for every recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who do not know it.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario sets a damaging precedent for all national companies with branches in the neighboring country and with solvency problems.
Therefore, it seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas on June 15 leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s leading glassmaker to sue the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the trial judge points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is commercial bankruptcy formalized in Mexico.
